  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/97655504?book_show_action=true">Apr 08, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lisa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lisa" href="/user/show/3191832-lisa">Lisa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3191832-lisa?shelf=mysteries-and-thrillers">mysteries-and-thrillers</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer97655504" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15885728755047606921">I&apos;m kind of torn over this book. I guess I&apos;ll give it three stars, because I really liked it, but it had a very weird angle and I&apos;m not really sure what to think about it. I really loved the parts with Birgitta. She was definately the stand-out character. I also thought the Chinese flash-back part was pretty interesting too. But then we move over to present-day China, and while the parts with Birgitta were great, once she leaves the picture and we&apos;re left with Hong Qiu and Ya Ru, things get weir</span>
  <span id="freeText15885728755047606921" style="display:none">I'm kind of torn over this book. I guess I'll give it three stars, because I really liked it, but it had a very weird angle and I'm not really sure what to think about it. I really loved the parts with Birgitta. She was definately the stand-out character. I also thought the Chinese flash-back part was pretty interesting too. But then we move over to present-day China, and while the parts with Birgitta were great, once she leaves the picture and we're left with Hong Qiu and Ya Ru, things get weird. Normally I'd like a little communist action thrown in there to spice everything up, but I thought it fell flat here and felt kind of forced. I found that the author was repeating himself over and over again. I was like, how many times must I read Hong Qiu's internal dialouge of the foundations and principles are superiority of the Chinese system of gov. and the genius that is all things Mao? So I give it three stars. The actual mystery was kind of thin. But the narration was really good and the character of Birgitta was very well developed. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15885728755047606921" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


