              <span id="reviewTextContainer3280491641" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17647561785618176093">I thought this would be slow-burning masterpiece, and Mr. Mankell almost delivered. There is a truly impressive, sweeping span of history and politics in this work. Where it came unstuck is in some parts towards the end, which just did not make sense. <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[ One action taken by the main character resembled the choice that characters in horror films often make - to step out in the dark, alone. You can&apos;t help thinking that an average person would know better. And then there&apos;s the matter o</span></span>
  <span id="freeText17647561785618176093" style="display:none">I thought this would be slow-burning masterpiece, and Mr. Mankell almost delivered. There is a truly impressive, sweeping span of history and politics in this work. Where it came unstuck is in some parts towards the end, which just did not make sense. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ One action taken by the main character resembled the choice that characters in horror films often make - to step out in the dark, alone. You can't help thinking that an average person would know better. And then there's the matter of how an assassination is committed in London, which was even more unbelievable.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />I wish the author had had an editor or a sparring partner who could have helped keep the turn of events sane.</span>
